<protolog id="rid.226_nm.5520" type="description" xmlns="http://namesforlife.com/ns/protolog" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" xsi:schemaLocation="http://namesforlife.com/ns/protolog file:/C:/NamesforLife/workspace/namesforlife-schema/protolog.xsd"><organism doi="10.1601/nm.5520" rank="genus">Trichococcus</organism><reference id="rid.226"><citation citation-type="journal"><authors><person-name><surname>Scheff</surname><given-names>G.</given-names></person-name><person-name><surname>Salcher</surname><given-names>O.</given-names></person-name><person-name><surname>Lingens</surname><given-names>F.</given-names></person-name></authors><article-title>Trichococcus flocculiformis gen. nov. sp. nov. A new Gram-positive filamentous bacterium isolated from bulking sludge.</article-title><year>1984</year><volume>19</volume><fpage>114</fpage><lpage>119</lpage><source id="423">Applied Microbiology and Biotechnology</source><abbrev>Appl Microbiol Biotechnol</abbrev><issn>0175-7598</issn><essn>1432-0614</essn></citation></reference><content><p class="title"><s>Description of <i>Trichococcus</i> gen. nov.</s></p><p class="etymology"><s><i>Trichococcus</i> Gr. n. <i>thrix</i> hair; Gr. n. <i>coccus</i> a grain or berry; <i>Trichococcus</i> a hair of cocci.</s></p><p class="description"><s>Cells spherical to ovoid, long filaments, no single cells, immobile, gram-positive, no spore formation.</s><s>Pellicles are formed in liquid culture when grown without shaking, forms small flocs when grown with shaking.</s></p><p class="description"><s>Faeultative anaerobes.</s><s>Benzidine-negative, catalase and oxidase-negative.</s></p><p class="description"><s>Minimal nutritional requirements are generally complex.</s></p><p class="description"><s>Type species: <i>Trichococcus flocculiformis</i>.</s></p></content></protolog>